1
00:00:42,136 --> 00:00:44,789
[ crunches ]
[ tires screech ]

2
00:00:47,277 --> 00:00:48,406
[ engine stops ]

3
00:01:01,782 --> 00:01:04,093
Professor: — Today’s discussion is postponed,

4
00:01:04,094 --> 00:01:06,817
as we have a very special guest.

5
00:01:06,818 --> 00:01:08,458
He’s played an instrumental part

6
00:01:08,459 --> 00:01:10,904
in the world debut of the IBM PC,

7
00:01:11,018 --> 00:01:12,609
which is now on the verge of becoming

8
00:01:12,610 --> 00:01:15,787
the industry standard for corporate America.

9
00:01:15,788 --> 00:01:19,350
Please welcome Mr. Joseph MacMillan.

10
00:01:19,351 --> 00:01:22,748
[ students applauding ]

11
00:01:22,749 --> 00:01:26,182
Let me start by asking a question.

12
00:01:26,183 --> 00:01:29,412
How many of you desire to be computer engineers ?

13
00:01:29,776 --> 00:01:30,933
Hmm.

14
00:01:30,983 --> 00:01:32,399
[ music playing faintly ]

15
00:01:32,400 --> 00:01:34,569
Oh… glad you could join us.

16
00:01:36,067 --> 00:01:38,120
MacMillan: Keep your hands up, keep your hands up.

17
00:01:38,121 --> 00:01:39,901
Now I’m going to list off several categories.

18
00:01:39,902 --> 00:01:42,616
When you hear a category you don’t
have hands-on experience in…

19
00:01:42,617 --> 00:01:44,262
[ music stops ]
— Put your hand down.

20
00:01:44,263 --> 00:01:45,890
Software design.

21
00:01:46,394 --> 00:01:48,656
Hardware/software integration.

22
00:01:48,739 --> 00:01:51,115
Circuity design. Microprocessing.

23
00:01:51,116 --> 00:01:55,129
Firmware design. Very large-scale integration.

24
00:01:55,231 --> 00:01:57,374
[ chuckles ]
— Something funny ?

25
00:01:57,375 --> 00:02:00,080
I don’t thing you really know what that is.

26
00:02:00,081 --> 00:02:00,946
Why ?

27
00:02:00,947 --> 00:02:03,688
Because nobody who knows what it is calls it that.

28
00:02:03,689 --> 00:02:06,754
“VLSI.” How’s that ?

29
00:02:08,249 --> 00:02:10,117
Operating systems.

30
00:02:10,248 --> 00:02:15,085
P-ROM conﬁguration and PLC design.

31
00:02:15,970 --> 00:02:20,568
Personal computer design. Very good.

32
00:02:20,940 --> 00:02:22,541
Now, tell me one thing that will be true

33
00:02:22,542 --> 00:02:24,772
about computers 10 years from now.

34
00:02:25,065 --> 00:02:27,129
Well, fully intelligent machines

35
00:02:27,130 --> 00:02:30,361
will simulate the actions of
neurons more closely, replicate…

36
00:02:30,362 --> 00:02:33,284
Okay, thanks. You.

37
00:02:33,285 --> 00:02:37,921
Uh, computers will be connected together across one network

38
00:02:37,922 --> 00:02:39,332
with a standard protocol.

39
00:02:39,333 --> 00:02:42,606
— Like phone lines.
— Obviously phone lines.

40
00:02:42,607 --> 00:02:45,414
— What’s your name ?
— Cameron.

41
00:02:45,737 --> 00:02:47,510
Cameron Howe.

42
00:02:48,120 --> 00:02:50,064
[ music playing ]

43
00:02:50,065 --> 00:02:52,433
So, you graduate this year.

44
00:02:52,449 --> 00:02:54,744
You land a job, become a programmer for what,

45
00:02:54,745 --> 00:02:58,561
what do you wanna do ? Microcode ? PCs ? Video games ?

46
00:02:58,582 --> 00:02:59,866
Do you need a quarter ?

47
00:03:00,371 --> 00:03:02,365
— Got it.
— Nice.

48
00:03:07,396 --> 00:03:10,626
I want to work for Reagan’s Strategic Defense Initiative

49
00:03:10,627 --> 00:03:12,409
and put missiles in space.

50
00:03:12,410 --> 00:03:14,813
Are you afraid to give me a straight answer ?

51
00:03:15,019 --> 00:03:17,872
[ video game rumbles ]
— A straight answer ? Uh, let’s see.

52
00:03:18,326 --> 00:03:21,804
Everything I’m studying here is so totally 10 years ago

53
00:03:21,805 --> 00:03:23,925
that no one who matters pays attention to anything I do.

54
00:03:23,926 --> 00:03:26,404
— I’m paying attention.
— Yeah, but do you matter ?

55
00:03:26,734 --> 00:03:28,764
Hey, can we get two more ?

56
00:03:28,849 --> 00:03:30,698
Would you know if I did ?

57
00:03:31,545 --> 00:03:34,473
What is this anyway, some kind of job interview ?

58
00:03:34,474 --> 00:03:36,829
Maybe, maybe now. Depends on you.

59
00:03:38,424 --> 00:03:39,742
[ machine clattering ]

60
00:03:39,743 --> 00:03:41,537
You still haven’t answered my question.

61
00:03:41,538 --> 00:03:43,728
Does it even matter what I want to do ?

62
00:03:43,746 --> 00:03:45,617
God, this is an industry built on people

63
00:03:45,618 --> 00:03:48,097
ripping off each other’s boring-ass ideas.

64
00:03:48,184 --> 00:03:51,212
SCP rips off CP/M, Microsoft rips off SCP.

65
00:03:51,213 --> 00:03:52,895
Oh, IBM rips off everybody, right ?

66
00:03:52,896 --> 00:03:54,006
You’ve got a lot of excuses.

67
00:03:54,007 --> 00:03:56,273
And you work for IBM !

68
00:03:56,274 --> 00:03:59,426
Hey, computers could be more. They should be.

69
00:03:59,427 --> 00:04:03,466
You build counting machines, the same
thing you’ve done for the last 70 years.

70
00:04:03,679 --> 00:04:05,622
I don’t work for IBM.

71
00:04:14,671 --> 00:04:16,361
[ bangs ]

72
00:04:20,563 --> 00:04:22,947
[ moaning ]

73
00:05:10,199 --> 00:05:12,860
This doesn’t mean you get the job.

74
